post_text:
Dear Patron,

Recently, the Fremont County School District was fortunate to receive a grant to study how we can improve the educational offerings for our children between the ages of 0 and 5. We have referred to this as the “crib to kindergarten,” or the Preschool Grant. In the upcoming weeks, we will be trying to determine the needs of our community regarding pre-school education and care. You will have the opportunity to answer some questions regarding what your needs are regarding educating this age group of children, and how our school district and community can help with these needs. We are especially interested in knowing how to better support those who currently offer preschools or daycare to our children. We would appreciate your input.

We have referred to this as the “crib to kindergarten,” or the Preschool Grant. You will have the opportunity to answer some questions regarding what your needs are regarding educating this age group of children, and how our school district and community can help with these needs. We are especially interested in knowing how to better support those who currently offer preschools or daycare to our children. We would appreciate your input.

post_text: Good afternoon, I just wanted to make sure everyone knew that our regular School Board meeting will be held via this Facebook page. Just like our two previous special board meetings, the board will attend via zoom, and it will be streamed live here on the district Facebook page. The regular May meeting has been moved to 11:30 am Thursday, with an executive session first. When the board enters executive session, streaming will stop, and streaming will begin again once the board returns to the open meeting. School Board meetings are not public meetings, but meetings held in public. Thank you all for your support for our schools. Our students are very fortunate to have great parents, teachers, and wonderful communities.

South Fremont High School
April 17 at 11:39 AM ·

￼ We have received official word from the IHSAA that all spring sports have been cancelled. We want to acknowledge all of the athletes and coaches. We especially want to recognize the senior class of 2020! It is hard not to have the opportunity to compete after preparing so long for this moment. As all of our coaches teach, when we have trials and adversity we will find a way to get through and move past this. We are so proud of the athletes, coaches, and families in our school and community. This is an amazing place to live and we always come together and help each other. If there are any questions or if you need any help let us know. When the time is right we will be in contact with the athletes and the coaches to address fee payments and to turn in uniforms and equipment. It’s a great day to be a Cougar!!

post_text:
Good morning,
This evening, at 7:00 pm MT, we will hold our regular April School Board meeting via live broadcast on this page. If you are interested in attending the board meeting, please do so here. The School Board will be in attendance via ZOOM. This will meet the requirements for COVID-19 social distancing and also the requirements for the open meeting law.
Since the meeting is not a public meeting, but a meeting held in public, comments will not be recognized. Thank you for your cooperation, patience, and support during these interesting times.
Also, Governor Little has continued our soft closure/home delivery until April 30, 2020. The State Board of Education has created guidance for our district to re-open. However, in looking at those guidelines, it does not appear we will be opening again. I hope I am wrong. Again, thank you for your cooperation, patience, and support! Please stay safe, healthy, and enjoy life. God bless!

post_text:
Good afternoon,

I hope this finds you all safe and healthy. Please take care of yourselves through these trying times. Together we can beat this, and our children will still gain a quality education. Don’t worry about them regressing in school. Every single child is in the same boat, and they will be okay. When we are back in the classroom, we will all course correct to meet their needs where they are. Our teachers are experts at this! Don’t pick fights with our kids because they are struggling to do their homework. Don’t scream at them for not following a perfect schedule. Don’t mandate learning, encourage it. If there is one thing of utmost importance, it is this; At the end of all of this, your children’s mental and physical health will be more important than their academic skills. Our teachers will get them up to speed if need be. How your children felt during this time will stay with them long after the memory of what they did during these weeks and months at home has passed. So keep in mind, enjoy every single day.

post_text:
I saw this post, and I need your help to make what we are doing be successful. It says my request so well. Thanks for your understanding and support.
..................................

Please offer grace to your child’s teacher and other school personnel. I promise, that educating your children is still our priority. ❤️

In the upcoming days we will start a new chapter in public education. There is a huge learning curve that students and teachers will be navigating together!!

As we embark on this thing called "remote learning,” I am asking my Facebook friends to refrain from publicly scrutinizing their children’s teachers/schools/district for the way they are teaching or the lessons they are assigning.

We are about to navigate uncharted waters with little, to no prep time. This is a crisis, not a time to be playing armchair quarterback. We love your kids, and we will be doing our absolute best!

❤❤❤❤❤❤❤❤

Please copy & paste if you are in education!

And fellow educators, you got this. I believe in you!

~ author of post unknown

post_text: Kudos to our Sheriff and for our great county for supporting him.
shared_text:
Fremont County Sheriff - Idaho
March 25 at 2:59 PM ·

We understand that at this time and with this recent 21 day stay-at-home order, that we have citizens within our community that fall into the "high Risk" category. Sheriff Humphries has authorized with some stipulations, the following services:

Medication pick up from a pharmacy- this will only work if you have paid via the phone, and then contact the sheriffs office once the prescription is ready to be picked up.
(all arrangements have to be done ahead of schedule)

Small grocery order pick ups - once again, if you can contact one of the following businesses and make pre-payment ahead of schedule. we can pick up and deliver to your door- our staff will not be permitted to enter the residence. (once again we are talking about "high risk".)

Dave's Jubilee- Ashton
Falls Drug- St. Anthony
Ashton Community Pharmacy
Robins Roost and Groceries
Broulims St. Anthony.

**you have to make sure that the business knows that the sheriffs office will be picking up the items/medications**

If you or someone you know fits into this category please call 208-624-4482.

post_text: Meet Mary Cory, teacher at South Fremont High School! She says, "This is my sixth year teaching in the Fremont School District and I have absolutely loved it! I work at South Fremont High School, and I teach 11th grade English and yearbook. For me, it is hard to choose just one thing that I love about this school. First of all, the leadership is very positive, which sets a great example for the entire staff. It is fun to work here. I am a very positive person and this greatly appeals to me.This also rubs off on the kids. Being positive is free and creates an environment of optimism about learning. I also love the students at this school. We have great kids here and I find them to be respectful and fantastic!" Thank you Mary for all you do! #thankyou

If you don't have internet access, please come to Fremont County Joint School District's office and visit with Jamie Hymas, Human Resources Director. It is a year round, full time positions with benefits. Pay determinate based on qualifications and experience.

South Fremont High School is with Renee Tucker.
December 4, 2019 at 5:52 PM ·

Congratulations to our Cougar Grit Award winners for the month of November. Malorie Tucker has jazz band at 7:00 am. Then after school would have basketball practice. After basketball practice she would go to play practice the rest of the night and then come home and do homework. Justin Angell was also in the play. He would have early morning wrestling practices before school and also put in time to run. We appreciate the hard work and time that Malorie and Justin put in to do so many things and the Cougar Grit they show. It’s a great day to be a Cougar!!

November 11, 2019 at 10:49 PM ·

A Huge Thank You to everyone that participated in the Veterans Day Assembly today at the High School. It was phenomenal. The speakers did a great job. The band and choir were extremely entertaining. But what was even more impressive was how reverent and respectful the students were. The gym was packed with High School, Jr High, and Elementary age kids and it was absolutely silent except for the presenters and performers the entire hour. Thank you to all those that attended. If you haven’t thanked a veteran yet today, pick up your phone and do so. #ItsAGreatDayToBeACougar
